  "signature": "ed25519:a1b2c3d4e5f6a7b8c9d0e1f2a3b4c5d6e7f8a9b0c1d2e3f4a5b6c7d8e9f0a1b2",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "SQA documentation must demonstrate version-controlled solver builds, regression test suites covering all active element types, and traceable change logs. Gradation 2 requires at minimum a formal QA plan and documented test coverage report.",
      "rationale": "The FEA ensemble employs Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 and an in-house FDA solver. Both codebases are maintained under ISO 9001-compliant quality management systems with documented regression test suites. Ansys provides a published verification manual; the FDA solver is governed by a software quality plan conforming to FDA 21 CFR Part 820. Version control is enforced via Git with tagged release commits. Gradation 2 is required given medium model risk; Gradation 3 is achieved because the ensemble additionally includes inter-code cross-verification results."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification must include at least one benchmark problem with known analytical solution demonstrating convergence at the expected theoretical rate for all element formulations used in the pedicle screw model.",
      "rationale": "Patch test and manufactured-solution benchmarks were executed for the hexahedral and tetrahedral element types used in the construct mesh. Convergence rates matched theoretical expectations (second-order for linear elements). Results are archived in the project verification report VR-2024-001."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "A formal mesh convergence study must demonstrate that QoI values change by less than 2% between the penultimate and final refinement levels, and a Richardson extrapolation-based GCI must be reported.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted on the screw-rod-vertebral body assembly. Global element size was reduced by factor 1.5 at each level. The Grid Convergence Index (GCI) for construct stiffness was 0.8%, well below the 2% threshold. Yield force GCI was 1.1%. Richardson extrapolation values are tabulated in Appendix B of the model documentation."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver residuals must be reported and must fall below 1e-6 for all load steps; energy balance must be confirmed within 0.5%.",
      "rationale": "Direct sparse solver (PARDISO) was used for all linear solution steps, eliminating iterative convergence concerns. Energy balance was verified at each load increment; maximum imbalance observed was 0.03%. Nonlinear convergence norms (force and displacement) dropped below 1e-8 at every increment."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model setup must be independently reviewed by a second analyst; boundary condition application and material assignment must be cross-checked against the governing test standard (ASTM F1717).",
      "rationale": "An independent senior analyst reviewed the boundary condition definitions, contact pair assignments, and material property inputs against the ASTM F1717-2015 standard. No discrepancies were identified. Review sign-off is recorded in the project quality record QR-2024-003."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model form adequacy must be supported by published literature or prior validation studies demonstrating that the chosen constitutive law and contact formulation are appropriate for metallic implant compression-bending at the relevant strain rates and magnitudes.",
      "rationale": "An isotropic linear-elastic constitutive model with Ti-6Al-4V properties (E=114 GPa, ν=0.34) is appropriate for the sub-yield regime explored in stiffness prediction. For post-yield QoIs, a bilinear isotropic hardening model calibrated from coupon tensile tests is employed. Frictionless surface-to-surface contact with augmented Lagrangian enforcement is used at the screw-rod interface, consistent with published benchmarks in spinal implant FEA literature (Goel et al., Rohlmann et al.). The model form selection is supported by three peer-reviewed validation studies at comparable load magnitudes."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties must be sourced from traceable coupon tests on production-lot material; geometric inputs must be derived from calibrated CMM measurements of the as-tested hardware.",
      "rationale": "Material properties were characterized from tensile coupon tests on the same production lot as the test constructs (n=5 coupons per lot). CMM measurements of screw and rod geometry were performed at DePuy Synthes metrology laboratory with calibrated equipment (uncertainty ±2 µm). Uncertainty in material inputs was propagated via Monte Carlo sampling (n=1000 runs) to quantify QoI sensitivity."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The experimental sample set must consist of at least 10 constructs from production-representative hardware; inter-laboratory reproducibility must be demonstrated across at least two independent test sites.",
      "rationale": "N=11 constructs were tested across two independent laboratories (FDA CDRH and DePuy Synthes internal lab). All hardware was drawn from the same production lot. Inter-laboratory coefficient of variation for construct stiffness was 3.2%, demonstrating acceptable reproducibility. Sample size exceeds the minimum of 10 specified for Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions must span the range of clinically relevant loading scenarios; at minimum, two distinct load configurations or offset distances must be evaluated to confirm model generalizability.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted at a single ASTM F1717 offset distance (100 mm). While this configuration is the standard regulatory condition, it does not span the full range of clinical loading scenarios. Only one test condition was evaluated, limiting the achieved level to Gradation 2. This shortfall is acknowledged; the model is considered adequate for the specific COU (regulatory submission under ASTM F1717) but not for broader load-case extrapolation."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "A formal equivalency mapping must document how each experimental input parameter (geometry, material, boundary conditions, loading rate) is represented in the simulation, with quantified uncertainty for each mapping.",
      "rationale": "A parameter equivalency table was constructed mapping 14 experimental inputs to their simulation counterparts. Geometric equivalency was verified via CMM-to-CAD comparison (max deviation 0.05 mm). Loading rate equivalency was confirmed by comparing quasi-static test rate (5 mm/min) to inertial effects estimated via Rayleigh damping analysis — dynamic effects negligible (<0.1% QoI change). All mappings are documented in the equivalency report EQ-2024-002."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "Quantitative output comparison was performed using the ASME V&V 40 validation metric E/uval for each QoI. For construct stiffness: E/uval = 1.12 (pass, threshold 1.96). For yield force: E/uval = 0.87 (pass). For force at 40 mm displacement: E/uval = 1.43 (pass). Additionally, percent difference between FEA ensemble mean and experimental mean was computed: stiffness 4.2%, yield force 6.8%, force at 40 mm 7.1% — all within the pre-specified 10% bound. The validation metric framework follows ASME V&V 40-2018 Section 9.4. Inter-laboratory variability was incorporated into the experimental uncertainty estimate using pooled standard deviation. All three QoIs pass both the E/uval criterion and the percentage bound criterion. The ensemble spread across the three FEA codes was also evaluated: maximum inter-code spread was 2.3% for stiffness, confirming that code-to-code variation is small relative to experimental uncertainty. Detailed comparison plots and tabulated results are provided in the validation report VR-2024-002, which has undergone internal peer review and regulatory review by FDA CDRH. The thoroughness of this comparison, spanning three independent QoIs, two acceptance metrics, and three FEA codes, provides strong evidence that the model form and inputs are adequate for the stated COU. No systematic bias was detected across the QoI set; residuals show no trend with construct number or test laboratory, indicating that the model captures the dominant physics without systematic error."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The selected QoIs must be directly linked to the regulatory decision criteria and must be demonstrated to be sensitive to the model inputs of greatest uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three QoIs specified in ASTM F1717 for regulatory comparison. Each QoI is directly referenced in the 510(k) submission pathway for pedicle screw systems. Sensitivity analysis (one-at-a-time and Sobol indices) confirmed that these QoIs are most sensitive to Ti-6Al-4V yield strength and rod diameter — the two inputs with the greatest material uncertainty. Relevance is therefore established both by regulatory definition and by quantitative sensitivity analysis."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The validation activities must use hardware and test protocols that are representative of the COU device and loading environment; any differences between the validation configuration and the COU must be explicitly documented and their impact on model credibility assessed.",
      "rationale": "The validation activities used production-representative non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screws tested per ASTM F1717 — the identical protocol and device configuration as the COU. No surrogate materials or simplified geometries were employed. The only noted difference is that the validation was conducted at a single offset distance (addressed under Test Conditions); this limitation is scoped and its impact on the COU is bounded by the single-condition regulatory requirement. The validation activities are therefore directly relevant to the COU."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-decision-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "All 13 V&V 40 credibility factors were assessed. Twelve of thirteen factors meet or exceed their required gradation level. One factor (Test conditions) achieves Gradation 2 against a required level of 3, reflecting the single-condition ASTM F1717 protocol; this shortfall is accepted because the COU is explicitly scoped to the F1717 regulatory configuration and does not require multi-condition generalizability. The overall credibility evidence is judged sufficient to support a Medium assurance level decision for the stated COU. The validation metric E/uval passes for all three QoIs, and no systematic model bias was detected.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
